07424nam a22007935i 9780226819631DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226819631  a(DE-B1597)625627  a(OCoLC)1305845833  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a331223/swe1 aFerreras, Isabelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocratize Work :bThe Case for Reorganizing the Economy /cJulie Battilana, Isabelle Ferreras, Dominique Méda. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (136 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: For a Fairer, More Democratic, Greener Society -- tManifesto: Work. Democratize. Decommodify. DECARBONIZE -- tFrom the Politically Impossible to the Politically Inevitable: Taking Action -- tDemocratize Firms . . . Why, and How? -- tEqual Dignity for All Citizens Means Equal Voice at Work: The Importance of Epistemic Justice -- tDemocratizing Work to Reverse Increasing Inequalities -- tWork in Dignity -- tDual Majorities for Firm Governments -- tRescuing Journalism by Decommodifying the Media -- tDecommodifying Work: The Power of a Job Guarantee -- tAll Workers Produce Value -- tThe Subaltern Worker-Body Speaks; Will the Privileged Listen? -- tSustaining Life on This Planet -- tWorking Against an End: Shifting Gears for a New Beginning -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn urgent and deeply resonant case for the power of workplace democracy to restore balance between economy and society. What happens to a society—and a planet—when capitalism outgrows democracy? The tensions between democracy and capitalism are longstanding, and they have been laid bare by the social effects of COVID-19. The narrative of “essential workers” has provided thin cover for the fact that society’s lowest paid and least empowered continue to work risky jobs that keep our capitalism humming. Democracy has been subjugated by the demands of capitalism. For many, work has become unfair. In Democratize Work, essays from a dozen social scientists—all women—articulate the perils and frustrations of our collective moment, while also framing the current crisis as an opportunity for renewal and transformation. Amid mounting inequalities tied to race, gender, and class—and with huge implications for the ecological fate of the planet—the authors detail how adjustments in how we organize work can lead to sweeping reconciliation. By treating workers as citizens, treating work as something other than an asset, and treating the planet as something to be cared for, a better way is attainable. Building on cross-disciplinary research, Democratize Work is both a rallying cry and an architecture for a sustainable economy that fits the democratic project of our societies. Contributors include Alyssa Battistoni (Barnard College of Columbia University), Adelle Blackett (McGill University), Julia Cagé (Sciences Po), Neera Chandhoke (University of Delhi), Lisa Herzog (University of Groningen), Imge Kaya Sabanci (IE Business School), Sara Lafuente (European Trade Union Institute), Hélène Landemore (Yale University), Flávia Máximo (Universidade Federal de Ouro Preto, Brazil), and Pavlina R. Tcherneva (Levy Economics Institute of Bard College).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCapitalism. 0aDemocratization. 0aIndustrial relations. 0aOrganizational justice. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ademocracy, democratic, economy, economics, reorganization, sociology, sociological, sociologists, labor, work, worklife, business administration, social innova